We went to 773 Lounge mostly because of Buffalo's Famous, which we had been to before, and really liked it. I'm not sure how much of my experience was the 773 Lounge and how much was the wings (so amazingly good), but we had a lot of fun. It's a nice, big space with enough seating. The cocktails were good--or rather, the first round was good and the second round was exceptional. One of their weeknight bartenders was around and ended up agreeing to make a few more craft cocktails for us. I feel like if they stepped up their cocktail game a bit (like a real cocktail menu, for one), this place could be five stars without the wings.

So I wanted to like this place, but I have mixed feelings. You need to know what it is, and what it is not. It's a bar with a food service in back operated by Buffalo's Famous (wings) if the drinkers get hungry. Husband and I went there entirely for the wings. We had eaten Buffalo's Famous wings when they had a their own shop on Church Ave, but that place closed and they moved in here. So far as I can see they do not offer delivery/Seamless etc. So the wings are great, but the bar is, well, just a kinda dumpy bar. The kind I used to hang out in in college but with more televisions, all playing football. No table service, at least not the night we were there (a Sunday). Order wings at the bar and they drop them off at your table later. Beer was basic. Bartender was pleasant but clearly we were not regulars, and there WERE regulars who looked like they had been there since the Clinton administration.  So make sure you want a bar that sells wings, not a restaurant that sells drinks. (The wings are great, btw!)

I never thought I would experience racism, personally. We (a group of well dressed Haitian Americans) went to a restaurant called 773 Lounge here in Brooklyn.  Upon waking in this restaurant we were greeted with the disrespectful comment "we don't serve chicken dinners here!"  Confusion on our face we didn't understand what the bartender said. One of us said, " Pardon? I don't understand". He repeated himself and said "we don't serve chicken here". I felt my heart breaking every second, after that racial stereotype.  Honestly, this guy burst my happy bubble. Before this I was hopeful for humanity and our human race. I don't want to take this experience and become jaded. I want to learn from this build up. I pray for this man and his heart. I pray that God serve mercy on him and his business.  God help us all!

Me and a group of church friends came to this restaurant. The guy didn't bother to say hi or ask us what we were there for. He just mentioned that there was NO CHICKEN!!! Honestly that was very RACIST!!!!!! I would never returned to this place neither recommend it to anyone that I know..

I'm only giving one star to be able to post a review. Horrible place; we went late on a Wednesday night, the bartender was incredibly racist to us. We are a young professional Puerto Rican couple; both of us are perfectly bilingual and have been living in Ditmas Park for the past 4 years. The Bartender was condescendingly making fun of my girlfriend's hispanic accent and claiming he couldn't understand her, asking her to speak slowly (she used to be an English teacher and now goes to grad school in NY...she can speak English...).  It was a huge disappointment to see this level of ignorance and bigotry in this lovely and diverse neighborhood. We really love living here and there is certainly no place for this Sh**t in Ditmas Park. We will not support this business at all and hope  that people who read this review feel the same way too. There are plenty of welcoming places in Ditmas Park, we don't need/want this.

I did have a chance to sample Lou's Homemade potato chips which were awesome. Jukebox plays cd's of music someone between 30 and 60 would like - No Rap.  Local bars can be iffy, on the night I stopped in all was good. I'll be back!

A huge slice of the native Brooklyn bar scene. Not your swanky Manhattan bar by any means. Dim, well worn, and reverberating with loud conversation from drunk locals, this place quintessential. I'm guessing it's a bit of a window into how Brooklyn was thirty years ago. Come for a stiff, remarkably cheap drink, have a smoke out back, and do some people watching. You'll definitely come in contact with some good specimines here.
